WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.520
Welcome to the test set. Here we talk with some of the brightest thinkers and tinkerers

00:00:06.520 --> 00:00:11.560
in statistical analysis, scientific computing, and machine learning, digging into what makes

00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:18.760
them tick, plus the insights, experiments, and OMG moments that shape the field.

00:00:18.760 --> 00:00:25.000
On this episode, we jam with Alenka Frim, mathematician-turned-yogi-turned-all-star-Apache-arrow-committer,

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:32.599
who notes that open-source and yoga's revolved side-angle pose have more in common than you think.

00:00:32.599 --> 00:00:40.599
Hey, everybody. Welcome to the test set. We're joined today by Alenka Frim, who's a data engineer and software developer

00:00:40.599 --> 00:00:49.799
and a committer to Apache Arrow and on the Project Management Committee, or PMC, and an Iyengar yoga teacher.

00:00:49.799 --> 00:00:58.919
And I'm joined by my two co-hosts, Hadley Wickham, who's chief scientist at Posit, and Wes McKinney, who's principal architect at Posit.

00:00:58.919 --> 00:01:11.040
And we're so excited to talk today. I feel like maybe one theme in hearing and in reading a little bit about you, Alenka,

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:18.360
is it seems like the theme of sort of how do open-source systems stay healthy?

00:01:18.360 --> 00:01:27.160
And sometimes they're big systems like Arrow, which sort of undergird a lot of data work and tools that people use.

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:31.199
So thanks so much for coming on the test set.

00:01:31.199 --> 00:01:38.160
Yeah, I thought maybe we could start today with just a little icebreaker, which might be maybe we could just go around.

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:48.559
And I'd be curious to hear from people, what do you think are like what's assigned to each of you of a healthy open-source community, would you say?

00:01:48.559 --> 00:01:54.760
I'm happy to go first. I'm, you know, I'm very interested in Alenka's take, especially after being involved in I mean,

00:01:54.760 --> 00:02:01.080
I'm also been very involved in Arrow since the beginning, but I've been less involved actively in the last five years.

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:08.839
And so I think Alenka's understanding and knowledge of the Arrow community is actually really interesting for this conversation,

00:02:08.839 --> 00:02:14.160
because I have a lot of experience like Arrow the first five years, Alenka, Arrow the last five years.

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:20.199
And so together we can really speak accurately to like what a whole 10 years of the Arrow project has looked like.

00:02:20.199 --> 00:02:30.520
But for me, like, I think the big signs are whether the community is adding people, like people are coming and staying.

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:45.119
And also, are members of the community comfortable raising concerns about what's not working and having constructive dialogue about how to fix it without blaming or pointing fingers?

00:02:45.119 --> 00:02:54.800
Yeah, I would definitely agree. I think what I see on Arrow, which I feel it shows of a healthy community,

00:02:54.880 --> 00:03:05.800
is the way we interact on GitHub, which is the main point of interaction, I would say, not only with PRs, but there's discussions, there is issues.

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:12.960
Together with the mailing lists, a mailing list, one is for developers, one is for users.

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:24.240
I feel there's a lot of motion, a lot of people raising questions, giving PRs, even reviews from a broader community, not just people you know.

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:28.759
And I think that's really shows and the communication is really so respectful.

00:03:28.759 --> 00:03:37.119
I'm not sure about, you know, open source in general, but my experience with Arrow is really, really positive in that sense.

00:03:37.119 --> 00:03:42.600
So I think that shows of health. I'm not I'm not sure how much Apache here influences.

00:03:42.600 --> 00:03:50.000
I think it has a strong like it stands on a strong foundation because it's under the Apache umbrella,

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:56.839
I would say, because there's already a structure that people know and they follow it.

00:03:56.839 --> 00:04:02.000
You know what, how to communicate, what's what's expected, what's not.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:09.720
So I think that's really helpful. The thing that like first came to my mind, like kind of building on what Wes says,

00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:14.600
but the first thing that came to my mind was like turnover, not just like adding new people.

00:04:14.600 --> 00:04:24.440
But I think it's also really healthy to have like people leave the community because that's like the sign that you've built something that's like more than just like one or two people.

00:04:24.440 --> 00:04:34.079
And I do think like one of the things we don't kind of talk about enough in general is like like kind of death as the part of like the life cycle,

00:04:34.079 --> 00:04:39.519
like not, you know, not death as in like the ending of things, but like people, you know, moving on to new things,

00:04:39.519 --> 00:04:44.399
changing roles, putting down things that they've had for that they've looked after over a long time.

00:04:44.399 --> 00:04:46.600
I think that's like super, super important.

00:04:46.600 --> 00:04:50.600
Yeah, it's so interesting that that aspect of people leaving.

00:04:50.600 --> 00:05:01.399
And I know, Wes, you mentioned like you were with Arrow for like you have some perspective on the first five years and Alenka came in for the last five years.

00:05:01.399 --> 00:05:11.160
Maybe to kick things off, Alenka, I'd be really curious to hear maybe a little bit about like what is Arrow and how did you get involved with it?

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:27.399
Well, Arrow in the core, the way I see it, the way I understand it now is a format that specifies an optimal way of saving data in memory so it can be analyzed

00:05:27.399 --> 00:05:37.880
the best, like the optimal way of analyzing versus having row by row as it's in conventional databases.

00:05:37.880 --> 00:05:40.760
But then this is just kind of an idea.

00:05:40.760 --> 00:05:44.399
I mean, the format, but then you have to build on it.

00:05:44.399 --> 00:05:49.359
So it's useful. And then there's so much languages connected to it.

00:05:49.359 --> 00:05:55.640
So it's not just a format. It's like a specification for languages, for applications.

00:05:55.640 --> 00:05:57.640
I mean, it's so, so broad.

00:05:57.640 --> 00:06:03.440
And then every implementation, every language has kind of a structure.

00:06:03.440 --> 00:06:11.279
So you can actually use data in memory or data on disk, you know, with this kind of format.

00:06:11.279 --> 00:06:13.079
So it's a really broad thing.

00:06:13.079 --> 00:06:18.160
I hope I kind of helped understand this because it's not something people use.

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:24.320
It's something that, you know, it's already there used by applications.

00:06:24.320 --> 00:06:40.320
So it's, they're faster and more optimal, but in the essence is just making things easier for a computer to, you know, calculate and analyze, you know, making it faster and more efficient.

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:54.279
It sounds like you're saying like a lot of people, even if they don't realize it, are probably using Arrow when they're doing like data analysis or maybe like querying a database or loading a file of data.

00:06:54.920 --> 00:06:59.079
The project is quietly crept into all corners of the data world.

00:06:59.079 --> 00:07:09.320
I actually just read a blog post on a data engineering substack titled Apache Arrow is eating the world, basically channeling, you know, Mark Andreessen's famous software is eating the world.

00:07:09.880 --> 00:07:11.279
And it's kind of true.

00:07:11.279 --> 00:07:21.519
Like, I think the, you know, if you look at the data ecosystem increasingly, like you look at the Venn diagram and you look at projects that support or use Arrow in some fashion, the ones that don't.

00:07:21.519 --> 00:07:26.720
And like the bubble that supports Arrow or uses it in some fashion has continued to grow.

00:07:26.720 --> 00:07:29.959
And the other bubble has shrunk as time has gone on.

00:07:29.959 --> 00:07:39.799
And so which has been, you know, I think very interesting to watch, but also I think it speaks to the to the credibility that the community has has built.

00:07:39.799 --> 00:07:59.920
And part of part of the credibility of an open source project like Arrow that you want everybody, all these hundreds of projects in open source and commercial projects to depend on is that they have to believe in the Arrow community to keep being healthy, to keep delivering good software because it has become this piece of critical infrastructure.

00:08:00.279 --> 00:08:12.440
And, you know, I think people like I think people like Alinka have been responsible for, you know, building building and developing the community to create that credibility that has led to the project's success.

00:08:12.440 --> 00:08:18.239
I admit that I've forgotten the details of how, you know, how we came to be connected and how you got involved in the project's beginning.

00:08:18.239 --> 00:08:26.920
But I think all that is, you know, very interesting to me because you started out as a contributor and have grown into, you know, a leading member of the community.

00:08:26.920 --> 00:08:34.760
And I think that's really interesting, you know, arc and your kind of your your growth as a, you know, open source community leader.

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:36.039
Can you paint the picture for us?

00:08:36.039 --> 00:08:42.440
Like, what what were you up to when you started contributing to Arrow?

00:08:42.520 --> 00:08:49.200
Well, the interesting thing is that I wasn't up to anything at that time.

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:57.039
I was solely teaching yoga for five years and doing nothing with computers.

00:08:57.039 --> 00:09:06.239
So, yeah, before I was working on this in the central bank as, you know, on a statistical department, just helping with anything they needed.

00:09:06.239 --> 00:09:10.640
And I graduated and I'm a mathematician.

00:09:10.640 --> 00:09:16.400
So when the pandemic hit, I had less, of course, less classes.

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:23.159
They were mostly online. I had a bit more time and I realized I missed something.

00:09:23.159 --> 00:09:25.719
So I started doing some research.

00:09:25.719 --> 00:09:30.239
What could be a nice way for me to get back into?

00:09:30.239 --> 00:09:35.000
I didn't know even what space, like is it data science, data analytics, data engineering?

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:41.320
I had no idea, but I wanted to try to see if, you know, it still intrigues me.

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:53.039
So when I started contributing to Arrow, I had no idea that in the meantime, Deployer happened because I was using R in central bank.

00:09:53.039 --> 00:09:57.080
You know, Pandas was big, but I haven't really used it before.

00:09:57.080 --> 00:10:00.719
So it was I was really kind of new.

00:10:00.719 --> 00:10:05.039
I had a friend that was working on Arrow at that time.

00:10:05.039 --> 00:10:09.599
So I was kind of brainstorming. We were brainstorming what what could I try?

00:10:09.599 --> 00:10:14.559
And open source sounded a great place because I wasn't looking for a job.

00:10:14.559 --> 00:10:20.280
I was looking for an opportunity to try out and to learn and to have fun.

00:10:20.280 --> 00:10:25.919
So I'm not sure why I picked Arrow. We talked about different things.

00:10:25.919 --> 00:10:29.119
I think I like hard problems.

00:10:29.119 --> 00:10:35.039
So I was really interested in if I can, you know, figure things out.

00:10:35.039 --> 00:10:43.520
The bad thing that I I mean, the bad thing, the thing I struggled with a bit was that I wasn't a user.

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:53.400
So I wasn't using Arrow in any sense. So it's kind of harder to understand it then because it's it will be much easier.

00:10:53.400 --> 00:11:00.280
But at the same time, I think the perspective I got from just trying to contribute was a different one.

00:11:00.280 --> 00:11:04.479
And it's also it has other positive things.

00:11:04.479 --> 00:11:12.960
So, yeah, when I started, I did some contributions to R because that was the language that was that I was most comfortable with.

00:11:12.960 --> 00:11:20.080
And I was just lucky that right after my fourth or fifth contribution,

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:26.039
we had a nice communication, nice collaboration with the R maintainers.

00:11:26.039 --> 00:11:33.039
There was a position open because there were grants. I think Ursa Labs got a grant from CZI.

00:11:33.039 --> 00:11:37.760
So it was just I think I was just at the right place at the right time, really.

00:11:37.760 --> 00:11:47.919
Just to give a little context to people who might not know about like what an R contribution to Arrow is, like what is a R contribution to Arrow?

00:11:47.919 --> 00:11:57.479
It can be different things. What I did was something that I thought would be the easiest, which is a binding.

00:11:57.479 --> 00:12:04.919
What that means is that our package, our Arrow package is connected to the C++ implementation.

00:12:04.919 --> 00:12:10.599
So you have a C++ code base that defines the format, the zero copying.

00:12:10.599 --> 00:12:15.760
It defines how to read parquet files, how to save them, all of that in C++.

00:12:15.760 --> 00:12:21.359
And then you don't have to do all of this magic again in R, you just kind of connect it.

00:12:21.359 --> 00:12:28.679
Right. So there's different layers and you have to just figure out what are the pieces of a puzzle that you are that you need.

00:12:28.679 --> 00:12:37.479
So my strategy was just look at, you know, PRs that were done before on the same on a similar thing and just try to figure out what's needed.

00:12:37.520 --> 00:12:45.719
You kind of mentioned earlier you weren't a user of Arrow, which they kind of made me wonder, like, who do you think is a user of Arrow?

00:12:45.719 --> 00:12:50.919
Like, I think of like Arrow is mostly this kind of like invisible technology, right?

00:12:50.919 --> 00:12:57.119
Like it succeeds because things just work and you don't, like ideally, I think you don't know that Arrow is being involved.

00:12:57.119 --> 00:13:02.280
It's just like, oh, I can use my data from wherever I'm working and wherever it lives.

00:13:02.280 --> 00:13:07.239
Like, who do you think of as the user, the users of Arrow?

00:13:07.239 --> 00:13:09.440
It also depends on the implementation, I think.

00:13:09.440 --> 00:13:21.239
But mostly for all, most of the Arrow implementations, the users are actually developers that build on, for example, you know,

00:13:21.239 --> 00:13:26.559
Query Engine uses this format and you just kind of, you know, build things on.

00:13:26.559 --> 00:13:39.840
Then you have Pandas, for example, trying to use PyArrow, so Arrow part of the kernels to do some of the things faster, better.

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:43.799
So, yeah, it's not an end user, I would say.

00:13:43.799 --> 00:13:51.159
Maybe in R package, that's a bit more usual to have an end user using it.

00:13:51.159 --> 00:14:00.280
But mostly, I mean, even in PyArrow, it's really interesting that a lot of PRs, a lot of pull requests,

00:14:00.280 --> 00:14:07.119
a lot of contributions are done by developers that have so much knowledge and they already know exactly what they need.

00:14:07.119 --> 00:14:14.000
They just, you know, make a PR and you're like, OK, I need a week to understand.

00:14:14.039 --> 00:14:26.119
So, yeah, these are experienced developers of applications that use, that it doesn't necessarily the application will be for the end user, but it can be.

00:14:26.119 --> 00:14:31.640
Sometimes it's already, it's also an application for an application, if that makes sense.

00:14:31.640 --> 00:14:40.000
So, yeah. I do remember one of the first meetings I had with Arrow project.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:47.960
I still remember what they said and they were saying that we are doing a good job if nobody knows about Arrow.

00:14:47.960 --> 00:14:55.960
Right, so it totally makes sense, but I still feel that people should know about Arrow.

00:14:55.960 --> 00:15:03.119
If not for general knowledge, for support, because, you know, if you don't know about Arrow,

00:15:03.119 --> 00:15:09.919
then how will people get support for maintenance and, you know, working on that?

00:15:09.919 --> 00:15:18.760
I mean, the way I've looked at it is I've told end users to, they don't need to know necessarily details of how to use Arrow or how to implement it,

00:15:18.760 --> 00:15:27.000
but rather when they're evaluating their other technology choices, that's something they should ask as part of their due diligence checklist is,

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:32.440
does this system support Arrow and or if it doesn't, is Arrow support on the roadmap?

00:15:32.440 --> 00:15:43.200
Because essentially that shows that a project is looking at the landscape of the open source ecosystem through like a progressive lens of like,

00:15:43.200 --> 00:15:52.119
this is something that it need not, it's not something that constrains systems necessarily, but it makes them more interoperable and more and more efficient.

00:15:52.119 --> 00:16:00.320
And so if there's a downstream project that doesn't see that kind of interoperability or that kind of performance improvement that Arrow provides,

00:16:00.320 --> 00:16:04.559
that that is, you know, for me, that's like a bit of a strike against the project.

00:16:04.559 --> 00:16:14.520
That's not necessarily like fully disqualifying, but definitely like, you know, it would make me second guess like a choice of a critical piece of data technology.

00:16:14.559 --> 00:16:23.640
It is an interesting challenge, though, like when you're, when an open source product like primarily exists to kind of remove pain, like people,

00:16:23.640 --> 00:16:30.200
like as soon as it kind of like percolate, like people kind of forget, oh, this is actually really annoying and frustrating to do before.

00:16:30.200 --> 00:16:35.719
And that just becomes normalized so quickly. And then like, how do you tell that story?

00:16:35.719 --> 00:16:43.840
Like, OK, you should support this project because it's actually making your life much like, like people don't really appreciate that story.

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:50.760
That's like when I was a, when I used to walk to school, it was, you know, it snowed every day and I had to walk uphill both ways.

00:16:50.760 --> 00:16:53.640
It's an interesting challenge.

00:16:54.599 --> 00:17:01.400
I'm not sure if necessarily developers or users need to know that or need to feel that.

00:17:01.400 --> 00:17:10.920
I think it's more on the managers and more on the leaders of this, you know, applications or companies.

00:17:10.920 --> 00:17:15.000
I think it's more on them to know the how serious this is.

00:17:15.479 --> 00:17:27.760
Yeah. And I guess maybe to make it concrete, too, for folks, there's that projects like like Polars uses Arrow and I think Pandas has Arrow support.

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:35.160
And I think Duck TV as well is is built on or largely as far as I understand, they are influenced.

00:17:35.160 --> 00:17:43.319
So they use the same format structure, but it's not something they they don't depend on Arrow per se.

00:17:45.119 --> 00:17:54.760
Yeah, Duck TV's internal internal data representation that it uses for all of its query processing is is very Arrow like and they actually early on,

00:17:55.719 --> 00:18:06.880
we we started working with Harness and Mark prior to even the existence of Duck TV Labs and the Duck TV Foundation to essentially figure out how to better align Duck TV with the Arrow ecosystem.

00:18:06.880 --> 00:18:13.400
And they did they did make changes in Duck TV to make the like the interface between Arrow and Duck TV work better.

00:18:13.400 --> 00:18:22.280
But without doing it in such a way that it didn't sacrifice performance, you know, in just only using Duck TV, I think they had the requirement.

00:18:22.280 --> 00:18:27.439
They're like, well, we don't want to make Duck TV slower in order to reduce the impedance mismatch with Arrow.

00:18:27.439 --> 00:18:35.199
And so they were able to find find a path where, you know, the bridge can think of it as like a bridge between, you know, between Arrow and Duck TV.

00:18:35.199 --> 00:18:41.079
It's not a totally free bridge, but it's like it, you know, they wanted to want the toll on the bridge to be as low as possible.

00:18:41.079 --> 00:18:48.599
And so the toll is is pretty you can, you know, query use Duck TV as an engine to process streams of Arrow data.

00:18:48.599 --> 00:18:56.319
And it's a it's it's a very, you know, one of the most effective ways to, you know, build a build an application nowadays.

00:18:56.319 --> 00:19:10.319
It may be it's easier for folks to understand these differences in if you think of Arrow specification, which is same or shared between, you know, Polar's Duck TV and Arrow project.

00:19:10.319 --> 00:19:17.239
So the idea is the same of how you store data and then just implementations themselves.

00:19:17.239 --> 00:19:24.920
You know, Arrow provides an implementation you can use or Duck TV has its own or, you know, Polar's has its own.

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:35.079
It's a Rust implementation, but because it's all the same spec, it's kind of we some people just say it's built on Arrow, but it's just compatible.

00:19:35.079 --> 00:19:46.959
How do you think about that? Like, it's always difficult to like specifications are hard to like narrow, like get every single like everyone agreeing on all these things that you don't like, think about when you're writing it.

00:19:46.959 --> 00:19:55.599
Like, like, how is that kind of specification and implementations of Arrow like co-evolved over time?

00:19:55.680 --> 00:19:58.359
I think that's a good question for Wes.

00:19:58.359 --> 00:20:15.199
I can say from how I'm observing it is you need to have a really good idea of how to make it in a way that people will be using it, you know, so it's kind of user friendly in a way.

00:20:15.199 --> 00:20:17.479
So they're like, OK, yes, and we can use that.

00:20:17.479 --> 00:20:28.880
It makes sense. And then also, I think what I see when working with Aaron is especially in PyArrow, because then separately, Python has a lot of specifications for interchange.

00:20:28.880 --> 00:20:33.319
You know, you have DLPAC, you have data interchange.

00:20:33.319 --> 00:20:34.719
I mean, there's a lot of them.

00:20:34.719 --> 00:20:36.160
So what's the difference?

00:20:36.160 --> 00:20:39.520
I think it's just when there's a need, something arises.

00:20:39.520 --> 00:20:45.359
And then with Arrow, I think the way community feels is that we're building something solid.

00:20:45.359 --> 00:20:48.599
And then if people need something different, that's fine.

00:20:48.599 --> 00:20:53.319
But the kind of the main thing is solid and we're going to work on it.

00:20:53.319 --> 00:20:58.280
And then more people adopt it, then it just kind of grows by itself.

00:20:58.280 --> 00:21:00.719
It's like spontaneous.

00:21:00.719 --> 00:21:09.199
I feel like we've hit so many interesting things, which is like Arrow is largely kind of like behind the scenes, driving a lot of stuff.

00:21:09.199 --> 00:21:14.760
It's hard for that to surface, like people might enjoy Arrow without even knowing it.

00:21:14.760 --> 00:21:19.439
And there's the question of like, how do you kind of support that kind of stuff?

00:21:19.439 --> 00:21:26.680
And then there's it's interesting to hear even like DuckDB, there's like the spec and people who might not just use Arrow,

00:21:26.680 --> 00:21:30.800
but maybe it might like rhyme with Arrow or they might keep Arrow in mind.

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:36.079
And how do you kind of like write a good specification?

00:21:36.079 --> 00:21:47.079
I one thing I thought I'd flag, too, is that I saw in a talk you gave before that Arrow has like thousands of issues open.

00:21:47.079 --> 00:21:50.400
Like there's tons of issues.

00:21:50.400 --> 00:21:55.199
We came under 4000 now with Nick Crane's help.

00:21:55.199 --> 00:21:58.560
Yeah, incredible.

00:21:58.560 --> 00:22:09.359
Are you using some some AI tools to help with like grouping and, you know, summarization, linking, linking, categorization and things like that?

00:22:09.359 --> 00:22:11.680
I haven't I haven't dared to use a I haven't yet.

00:22:11.680 --> 00:22:17.000
We're going through issues and like helping with like backlog, you know, curation.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:27.119
One thing Nick and I did was create a dashboard which surfaces, for example, issues that were not answered, issues that were opened by a new contributor.

00:22:27.119 --> 00:22:35.719
But because that's some things you want to kind of jump on first, same for PRs and etc.

00:22:35.719 --> 00:22:46.359
So that's what we use, which I think it's it's useful because otherwise what I tend to do is just answer things where I'm pinged because it's so much,

00:22:46.400 --> 00:22:47.319
you know, stuff going on.

00:22:47.319 --> 00:22:56.160
So I mean, here's like a this is I don't really mean this, but like like how can I trust a project that has like 4000 open issues?

00:22:57.599 --> 00:23:00.319
Like how do you think how do you think about that?

00:23:00.319 --> 00:23:01.920
Like it's the closed issues, Hadley.

00:23:01.920 --> 00:23:04.199
Look at how look how many look how many closed issues there are.

00:23:04.199 --> 00:23:06.599
Yeah, it's probably like 20000 closed issues.

00:23:06.599 --> 00:23:08.880
Yes. Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:23:09.040 --> 00:23:10.880
I mean, like what how do you think?

00:23:10.880 --> 00:23:19.839
Because I think I've like evolved this like pretty unusual way of dealing with issues just because, you know, I think fewer users are comfortable on GitHub.

00:23:19.839 --> 00:23:22.839
So the number of issues you get for an R package is much, much smaller.

00:23:22.839 --> 00:23:26.560
So I like this like the kind of inbox zero approach of issues.

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:33.920
Like, oh, to me, the ideal number of issues in a repository is like under 25 because that's like one page on GitHub.

00:23:34.640 --> 00:23:39.760
But that's like so like my I just can't even imagine like how do you think about that?

00:23:39.760 --> 00:23:45.760
Like when you think about those 4000 issues, like you just don't care that there's all these open issues.

00:23:45.760 --> 00:23:50.239
Like what like where's the like do you see them as being valuable or useful?

00:23:50.239 --> 00:23:51.760
Like what's like what's the point?

00:23:52.479 --> 00:23:56.800
Like I see the point of an issue is to be closed, I guess, but that's clearly not.

00:23:57.439 --> 00:24:01.439
If you look at the issues as bug reports, then yes.

00:24:02.160 --> 00:24:04.800
But there's a lot of feature requests in Arrow.

00:24:05.439 --> 00:24:09.280
There's a lot of documentation, you know, issues.

00:24:09.280 --> 00:24:12.079
There's user questions.

00:24:12.079 --> 00:24:14.479
I mean, it would be really nice to have zero.

00:24:14.479 --> 00:24:21.199
But I think it's important to understand the scope of Arrow.

00:24:21.199 --> 00:24:25.040
It's just it's not one project that we normally think of.

00:24:25.040 --> 00:24:27.199
It's so broad.

00:24:27.199 --> 00:24:33.040
Just maybe to put it in perspective, we have in the repo, we have multiple languages.

00:24:33.040 --> 00:24:37.599
And every language is for a couple of projects, right?

00:24:37.599 --> 00:24:40.239
It's, you know, in Python, it's just one part.

00:24:40.239 --> 00:24:45.439
And you have C++, you have R, you have I'm not really sure how many languages are still there.

00:24:45.439 --> 00:24:49.439
But because there's some of them are separate to make it easier.

00:24:49.439 --> 00:24:55.680
And then per language, you have so much parts of the implementation.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:00.239
You have, for example, in Python, in PyArrow, you have a part of the code base that deals

00:25:00.239 --> 00:25:02.400
with pandas compatibility.

00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:03.920
So you have issues for that.

00:25:03.920 --> 00:25:05.599
Then you have issues for file systems.

00:25:05.599 --> 00:25:10.880
And it's just such a broad thing that we're not stressing about it.

00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:16.160
We would like to have them all, not all closed, because there's always going to be something

00:25:16.160 --> 00:25:19.520
that will need to be done in Arrow, I think.

00:25:19.520 --> 00:25:21.280
Because it's an involving thing.

00:25:21.280 --> 00:25:26.880
It's not a project that it's just, you know, there and it will be used.

00:25:26.880 --> 00:25:28.400
It's more like it's developing.

00:25:28.400 --> 00:25:32.000
There's no new data types, you know, being included.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.160
There's some new things like parquet.

00:25:34.160 --> 00:25:39.199
You know, you have a specific code part where you deal with parquet reading and writing.

00:25:39.199 --> 00:25:41.119
So parquet is being evolved.

00:25:41.119 --> 00:25:42.959
And, you know, you have to match that.

00:25:42.959 --> 00:25:50.400
So I think it's, yeah, you have to have a different mindset for Arrow project versus

00:25:50.400 --> 00:25:51.199
other packages.

00:25:52.239 --> 00:25:57.280
I mean, the way I look at it is every like each language implementation of Arrow is aside

00:25:57.280 --> 00:26:01.280
from the ones that are a little more like wrapper layers like R and Python.

00:26:01.280 --> 00:26:05.199
But you can think of them as almost being like little operating system kernels for low

00:26:05.199 --> 00:26:07.119
level, low level data operations.

00:26:07.119 --> 00:26:12.160
And so, like, I mean, it's not exactly, you know, as grandiose as like, oh, a Linux kernel

00:26:12.160 --> 00:26:13.439
for data like that.

00:26:13.439 --> 00:26:14.800
That would be a silly way to market it.

00:26:14.800 --> 00:26:16.880
But it's kind of true in a way.

00:26:16.880 --> 00:26:22.479
And I think like the set of like that toolbox is like that.

00:26:22.479 --> 00:26:26.079
I think we always envision the project is like building on the specification.

00:26:26.079 --> 00:26:32.959
But like the specification alone is only so useful without like the toolbox and the framework

00:26:32.959 --> 00:26:36.400
of things that you need to build real world systems.

00:26:36.400 --> 00:26:42.160
And as time has gone on, I think that that toolbox has grown and sometimes has expanded

00:26:42.160 --> 00:26:45.920
in ways where we've been like, oh, maybe that was a mistake to like take on that piece.

00:26:45.920 --> 00:26:49.680
And like we've pruned, I think the project has pruned things that were like not getting

00:26:49.680 --> 00:26:54.640
maintained or that there just wasn't that much community interest in continuing to keep

00:26:54.640 --> 00:26:58.079
around or maybe spinning off into a side project.

00:26:58.079 --> 00:27:06.640
But it's been a little bit of like, I think, Neil, we had an Arrow summit in Paris at PyData

00:27:06.640 --> 00:27:07.599
Paris.

00:27:07.599 --> 00:27:14.719
And I think Neil Richardson described Arrow as a bit of a radical social experiment.

00:27:14.719 --> 00:27:19.199
And and so it's I do feel that way.

00:27:19.199 --> 00:27:24.959
And some of some of that, like the anarchy of like the sprawling, federated nature of

00:27:24.959 --> 00:27:29.680
the project has been, you know, certainly makes things more complicated, but also, I

00:27:29.680 --> 00:27:33.920
think, has helped keep the community together and keep it thriving and productive.

00:27:33.920 --> 00:27:40.880
I mean, it seems like you've really latched onto Arrow as a contributor and done so much

00:27:40.880 --> 00:27:44.479
for the ecosystem and an open source.

00:27:46.319 --> 00:27:51.520
I'm really curious, like how what do you think are like the ingredients to really get started

00:27:51.520 --> 00:27:52.400
with something like that?

00:27:52.400 --> 00:27:58.800
Like how does someone like get a foot into contributing and succeed at doing that kind

00:27:58.800 --> 00:27:59.199
of thing?

00:28:00.079 --> 00:28:05.520
I think to get started, you have to I don't know what would be the motivation.

00:28:05.520 --> 00:28:08.479
I think everybody has a different reason.

00:28:09.359 --> 00:28:17.760
But I think more I think of it, the more I talk to people, it's mainly experience or

00:28:17.760 --> 00:28:23.280
to grow or to learn or to just, you know, interact with, you know, a new community.

00:28:23.280 --> 00:28:26.319
I think I think mainly that is that.

00:28:27.199 --> 00:28:31.439
I mean, there's for sure a lot of contributors, especially in Arrow, where, you know, they

00:28:31.439 --> 00:28:38.560
use the tool and they need some feature or some bug fixed, which is so awesome in open

00:28:38.560 --> 00:28:41.839
source that you can actually have the possibility to do that.

00:28:41.839 --> 00:28:45.599
It's not like I'm waiting for somebody to fix my problem.

00:28:45.599 --> 00:28:51.359
It's like you have the option to do that and not just for you, but for somebody else, for

00:28:51.359 --> 00:28:51.599
sure.

00:28:53.040 --> 00:28:55.680
So how to succeed, I think.

00:28:56.400 --> 00:29:03.199
Well, I'm not sure if I would succeed without people around me that helped.

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:08.160
I mean, I did have to do the work and do the research and just stick with it.

00:29:08.160 --> 00:29:14.800
But just building Arrow from source locally, it's not an easy thing to do.

00:29:15.359 --> 00:29:20.880
And if I wouldn't have somebody helping me, I I'm it's quite possible that I wouldn't

00:29:21.680 --> 00:29:22.479
continue.

00:29:22.880 --> 00:29:23.439
Continue.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:29.439
So having this group and just having, you know, people encourage you in I think it was

00:29:29.439 --> 00:29:34.079
my third or second contribution that I was already paying like, oh, are you interested

00:29:34.079 --> 00:29:35.359
in doing this, too?

00:29:35.359 --> 00:29:40.800
And this means so much because you're like, oh, my God, they noticed me.

00:29:40.800 --> 00:29:42.880
It's in a project like this.

00:29:42.880 --> 00:29:44.719
It's amazing feeling.

00:29:44.719 --> 00:29:50.160
So small things like that when somebody would think it's not it's maybe even rude to ping

00:29:50.160 --> 00:29:50.560
people.

00:29:50.560 --> 00:29:51.040
It's not.

00:29:51.040 --> 00:29:56.640
It's it's like you show somebody that they're worth, you know.

00:29:57.839 --> 00:30:01.040
To collaborate with and to put some trust in them.

00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:06.400
Yeah, I could see like if you get pinged, it really shows like just realizing that people

00:30:07.199 --> 00:30:11.520
appreciated it and like noticed it like really makes it nice.

00:30:12.640 --> 00:30:17.839
And I wonder if related to I saw you gave a keynote and I think you gave the keynote

00:30:17.920 --> 00:30:19.439
a keynote in Paris.

00:30:19.439 --> 00:30:20.800
Yeah, which is awesome.

00:30:21.359 --> 00:30:22.560
Yeah, it was fun.

00:30:22.560 --> 00:30:29.359
And I saw one thing you talked about, too, was imposter syndrome, like how to sort of

00:30:29.359 --> 00:30:32.479
approach that as a as a person in open source.

00:30:34.719 --> 00:30:36.000
I'm curious your thoughts like what?

00:30:37.119 --> 00:30:41.680
Yeah, what what would you say is kind of the takeaway for people experiencing imposter

00:30:41.680 --> 00:30:47.199
syndrome and in and looking to contribute an open source?

00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:53.359
Yeah, one thing worth mentioning maybe is that.

00:30:54.640 --> 00:31:01.680
I you're not the only one feeling imposter syndrome, I think it's a really like a lot

00:31:01.680 --> 00:31:06.400
of people feel that when I think when I talk to people, when I talk to people after the

00:31:06.400 --> 00:31:11.680
keynote, when I talk to people I work with, which I feel they are the most brilliant people

00:31:11.680 --> 00:31:12.479
I've ever met.

00:31:12.479 --> 00:31:16.880
And they are saying that I feel I feel I don't understand.

00:31:16.959 --> 00:31:18.160
I feel I'm not capable.

00:31:20.479 --> 00:31:24.640
I would I would say a lot of people feel that and how to overcome.

00:31:27.439 --> 00:31:32.719
Well, again, maybe I'm repeating myself, but having somebody to you could talk to.

00:31:33.680 --> 00:31:35.119
I talked to Raul a lot.

00:31:35.119 --> 00:31:42.959
It was a Pyro, our friend, a contributor and a PMC member.

00:31:43.920 --> 00:31:47.119
He's involved in the project a lot.

00:31:47.119 --> 00:31:54.400
I'm talking to Nick on a regular basis, also a contributor, and we see that it's a common

00:31:54.400 --> 00:31:56.239
thing, which maybe it shouldn't be.

00:31:56.239 --> 00:32:03.199
But I guess I don't know if it's open source related or is just technology related or is

00:32:03.199 --> 00:32:05.040
that happens in general with people?

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:10.160
Because you're you're working with a lot of folks, you see what they do.

00:32:10.160 --> 00:32:14.319
You see it's there is something amazing and you always kind of want to match.

00:32:14.880 --> 00:32:21.040
But I think the real thing you need to do is find something you like and you feel comfortable

00:32:21.040 --> 00:32:24.719
and you feel motivated to do and you feel, you know, you have fun.

00:32:24.719 --> 00:32:30.400
And then after a while, you have to you have to look back at what all of the things you

00:32:30.400 --> 00:32:35.359
did, not just like looking and comparing to others, but saying to yourself and maybe having

00:32:35.359 --> 00:32:39.839
a friend so you can talk to and they will say, look, this is amazing what you did.

00:32:40.640 --> 00:32:45.839
That's also something I experience in Arrow is people stop, they talk to you and they

00:32:45.839 --> 00:32:48.959
say, Alenka, this is amazing work you did.

00:32:50.319 --> 00:32:57.040
And it really kind of all the bad emotions you feel, they tend to go away.

00:32:59.680 --> 00:33:00.479
Yeah, I don't know.

00:33:00.479 --> 00:33:02.800
I was really intrigued by Dr.

00:33:02.800 --> 00:33:03.599
Kat Hicks.

00:33:03.599 --> 00:33:07.599
She was doing keynote in Posit at Posit conference.

00:33:07.599 --> 00:33:14.560
So that was a lot of kind of research I did there for the for the for my keynote.

00:33:14.560 --> 00:33:16.479
I wasn't talking a lot about imposter system.

00:33:16.479 --> 00:33:21.359
I was just mentioning it and mentioning that we need to talk about it and do some research

00:33:22.400 --> 00:33:25.680
because I think it's really important for us to talk about that.

00:33:26.319 --> 00:33:27.680
And, yeah, Dr.

00:33:27.680 --> 00:33:30.880
Kat Hicks has a lot of good ideas on how to tackle that.

00:33:31.520 --> 00:33:37.359
So one thing I want to mention before I stop with this part is that at the Arrow community

00:33:37.359 --> 00:33:43.680
now we're talking about I'm doing the still reading about what they're researching and

00:33:43.680 --> 00:33:49.359
we're talking about what could we do as a process in the community that would help

00:33:50.880 --> 00:33:53.040
kind of remove this feelings.

00:33:53.040 --> 00:34:01.280
So one thing we are trying to do now is to make a blog post of highlighting contributions,

00:34:01.280 --> 00:34:05.680
you know, saying, OK, this is you know, this was a new contributor and they did amazing

00:34:05.680 --> 00:34:09.040
or this is such an amazing job done by somebody.

00:34:09.040 --> 00:34:10.399
I think that would help.

00:34:13.040 --> 00:34:18.000
Yeah, one of the things we've like in the when we do the release announcement for tidyverse

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:22.719
packages, we do just like a roundup, like, you know, very kind of low effort.

00:34:22.719 --> 00:34:24.080
But we're at least like, hey, thanks.

00:34:24.080 --> 00:34:28.879
So like all of these people who have interacted with us on GitHub and even like, you know,

00:34:28.879 --> 00:34:33.439
we hear every now and then people are like, oh, that's really cool to see my name or like

00:34:33.439 --> 00:34:37.360
when people have done like pull requests for the Alpha Data Science book, they get

00:34:37.360 --> 00:34:38.800
mentioned in the intro like that.

00:34:39.919 --> 00:34:42.000
It's small and obviously you can do much more.

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:46.959
But even like little gestures like that, I think people appreciate being recognized and

00:34:46.959 --> 00:34:47.679
acknowledged.

00:34:47.679 --> 00:34:48.239
Very much.

00:34:49.120 --> 00:34:56.320
And maybe also, you know, we don't all have to be, you know, Hadley and Wes, you know,

00:34:57.120 --> 00:35:00.399
it's fine if we you're not the core developer.

00:35:00.399 --> 00:35:05.919
It's fine if you don't feel comfortable in doing something, but you feel comfortable in

00:35:05.919 --> 00:35:06.879
doing something else.

00:35:07.840 --> 00:35:11.360
I think we have to realize that we don't have to know everything.

00:35:12.959 --> 00:35:14.959
And then you start learning.

00:35:14.959 --> 00:35:18.239
And then if you have fun, you kind of see that you actually know a lot.

00:35:18.800 --> 00:35:20.080
Yeah, it seems really neat, like.

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:28.959
Acknowledging contributors and also like emphasizing to people like you don't have to be the

00:35:28.959 --> 00:35:34.080
best, like figure out what about this you like and, you know, like why is this fun or

00:35:34.080 --> 00:35:34.959
interesting to you?

00:35:35.760 --> 00:35:36.639
It is interesting.

00:35:36.639 --> 00:35:41.280
Like I think like when you teach your like when you teach a workshop or you TA a workshop

00:35:42.159 --> 00:35:46.479
and like even if you're like, oh, like you feel like often like if you're TAing your

00:35:46.479 --> 00:35:50.000
first workshop, you feel kind of insecure in your knowledge.

00:35:50.800 --> 00:35:54.959
But then you realize like when you go and help people like the people taking the workshop

00:35:55.040 --> 00:35:57.439
and they're like, look, no, like literally nothing.

00:35:57.439 --> 00:35:58.800
And you like that.

00:35:58.800 --> 00:36:03.439
It's so like reinforcing to you like how valuable.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:08.320
Yeah, it shows how much you grown and how much you learned, actually.

00:36:09.840 --> 00:36:14.800
Yeah, and I kind of experienced this afresh recently.

00:36:14.800 --> 00:36:17.760
Like I taught my first yoga class.

00:36:18.399 --> 00:36:21.760
Like I subbed for my teacher and she like prepared the class.

00:36:21.760 --> 00:36:22.879
I just like gave it.

00:36:23.439 --> 00:36:27.840
But one thing that I found fascinating was like I've always been like, you know, how

00:36:27.840 --> 00:36:30.399
does a yoga teacher know how to do adjustments?

00:36:30.399 --> 00:36:32.719
Like how do they know like to like all this?

00:36:33.760 --> 00:36:37.760
And I just kind of thought all that like and obviously some of it is like years of experience

00:36:37.760 --> 00:36:39.520
and knowledge of anatomy and training.

00:36:39.520 --> 00:36:43.360
But some of it is also you just look at people from outside their body and you're like, oh,

00:36:43.360 --> 00:36:48.800
my God, that like that looks like you're so wonky and off like and just having that like,

00:36:48.800 --> 00:36:52.719
oh, actually, this is not like it's not as complicated as I as I thought it

00:36:52.800 --> 00:36:58.639
was. It's such a like an empowering experience to be like, OK, like just being outside of

00:36:58.639 --> 00:37:01.280
a person can be like having that fresh perspective.

00:37:01.280 --> 00:37:05.520
You don't have to be that much more knowledgeable than them to be like helpful and useful and

00:37:05.520 --> 00:37:08.479
to make their journey a little nicer.

00:37:08.479 --> 00:37:12.000
Interesting thought where like if you're the person doing yoga, you might have the

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:14.959
thought like, how did the teacher know to adjust me?

00:37:14.959 --> 00:37:21.040
But once you're the teacher, you're like, well, I'm seeing like 20 people and it stands

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:22.239
out.

00:37:24.560 --> 00:37:25.199
Let's see.

00:37:25.199 --> 00:37:29.840
I'm trying to think, oh, this is our chance to turn this into a podcast solely about yoga.

00:37:34.159 --> 00:37:40.159
But one I guess one interesting thing we could maybe turn to the group is I know you you

00:37:40.159 --> 00:37:44.159
mentioned a couple of questions that might be interesting to ask folks here.

00:37:46.159 --> 00:37:49.360
Maybe maybe this is kind of related to like yoga and learning.

00:37:50.159 --> 00:37:58.320
I think one thing you mentioned is like for learning, do people prefer to like learn as

00:37:58.320 --> 00:38:04.959
you go or to like stop and take a course to focus on things?

00:38:05.520 --> 00:38:07.199
Did I get that question right?

00:38:07.199 --> 00:38:08.639
Yes, yes, correct.

00:38:09.919 --> 00:38:11.919
Yeah, I'd be curious, folks, take on that.

00:38:13.199 --> 00:38:17.919
Like, do you think it's better to like when you want to learn something, do you prefer

00:38:17.919 --> 00:38:19.120
to stop and take a course?

00:38:19.600 --> 00:38:21.919
Or kind of like learn as you go?

00:38:23.760 --> 00:38:31.199
I like I teach a lot of workshops, but I have to say, like, I hate taking workshops myself

00:38:31.199 --> 00:38:34.879
because like the pace is set by someone else.

00:38:34.879 --> 00:38:39.679
Like, first of all, like, you know, now I'm like so used to watching like videos on YouTube

00:38:39.679 --> 00:38:41.679
at like one point five or two X speed.

00:38:41.679 --> 00:38:44.320
I'm like, why is this person talking so slowly?

00:38:44.320 --> 00:38:45.439
This is so inefficient.

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:50.080
And then that like that sort of inability to kind of like go on off on your own little

00:38:50.080 --> 00:38:51.520
learning tangent.

00:38:51.520 --> 00:38:54.320
So in some ways, like classes like feel.

00:38:56.159 --> 00:39:01.040
Like, so I don't know, like, yeah, like I don't enjoy that, but on the other hand, like

00:39:01.040 --> 00:39:05.280
I take yoga classes and that is something where I'm like, OK, I just it's just it's

00:39:05.280 --> 00:39:10.959
also nice just to be like told what to do every now and then and just here is a path

00:39:10.959 --> 00:39:12.959
like I have to like forge my own path.

00:39:12.959 --> 00:39:15.199
I'm just going to follow someone else's path.

00:39:15.280 --> 00:39:18.080
And that is like really nice sometimes to.

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:24.879
Yeah, for me, like I, I definitely prefer prefer hands on hands on learning where we're

00:39:24.879 --> 00:39:25.439
possible.

00:39:25.439 --> 00:39:32.000
And so whenever I dive into something new, I I will try to learn just enough to, you

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:37.360
know, be able to start start doing and then try to create a virtuous cycle of like doing

00:39:37.360 --> 00:39:41.120
and then running into the things that I don't know how to do and trying to figure it out

00:39:41.120 --> 00:39:46.399
and then, you know, kind of looping until and over the course of time, I guess that

00:39:46.399 --> 00:39:48.399
that that develops develops mastery.

