00:56:50.159 --> 00:56:55.280
that like on vacation, you thought like, it'd be neat to like try this out.

00:56:55.919 --> 00:57:00.879
Um, yes, I'm, I'm super curious, like what people end up building.

00:57:01.439 --> 00:57:05.439
Um, Wes, I saw you had a tool for code review.

00:57:05.439 --> 00:57:07.040
Is that, that's pretty recent?

00:57:07.040 --> 00:57:08.000
Yeah, just this week.

00:57:08.000 --> 00:57:13.520
I, um, I, yeah, I built a little tool called RoboRev in Go.

00:57:13.520 --> 00:57:15.600
And I've never written a line of Go in my life.

00:57:15.600 --> 00:57:16.159
True story.

00:57:16.719 --> 00:57:20.639
Uh, so Claude, you know, Claude helped me build it, build it in Go.

00:57:20.639 --> 00:57:26.159
And the idea is that it, uh, RoboRev, um, it runs a background as background service.

00:57:26.159 --> 00:57:30.959
And the idea is that if there's a repo that you're working in with, with agents, you,

00:57:30.959 --> 00:57:37.199
you run RoboRev in it and it will install a Git commit hook in the repository.

00:57:37.199 --> 00:57:40.879
And so whenever one of your agents, cause you might have multiple agents working in the same

00:57:40.879 --> 00:57:44.879
repo in the same branch, which I know is like, sounds crazy, but actually it's okay.

00:57:44.879 --> 00:57:46.959
If you ask them to work on distinct things.

00:57:47.600 --> 00:57:53.520
Um, but whenever one of the agents commits, um, immediately RoboRev will pick up the Git

00:57:53.520 --> 00:57:58.080
commit hook, will enqueue a review request, and you can choose the coding agent that you

00:57:58.080 --> 00:58:00.879
want to review that, that commit.

00:58:00.879 --> 00:58:06.399
And so basically it will kick off, you know, Claude or Codex or Gemini or Copilot with a

00:58:06.399 --> 00:58:10.239
prompt that includes, um, repo specific instructions.

00:58:10.239 --> 00:58:13.840
So maybe there's like, you know, guidelines around like what you want reviewed and what

00:58:13.840 --> 00:58:15.520
you care about, what you don't care about.

00:58:15.520 --> 00:58:20.560
And then it includes, um, if the diff is small, it includes the diff inline, other, which

00:58:20.560 --> 00:58:20.879
is good.

00:58:20.879 --> 00:58:25.760
Otherwise the LLM can hallucinate when it's, when it's inspecting the diffs with tool calls.

00:58:25.760 --> 00:58:30.320
But if the diffs are too big, then it will, you just let it use tool calls to look at

00:58:30.320 --> 00:58:32.800
the, look at the commits, uh, commit or commits.

00:58:33.360 --> 00:58:36.879
Um, and then, uh, basically it has a terminal user interface.

00:58:36.879 --> 00:58:42.239
So basically you can have, um, like I work with a stack of terminals and kitty terminal

00:58:42.239 --> 00:58:42.800
and Mac OS.

00:58:42.800 --> 00:58:46.399
So we'll have like four or five terminals stacked on top of each other.

00:58:46.399 --> 00:58:52.080
And so I've got like my robo rev, uh, terminal queue of reviews and then my agents that are

00:58:52.080 --> 00:58:52.479
working.

00:58:52.479 --> 00:58:57.760
And so basically an agent commits, the review triggers, it takes, you know, two to four

00:58:57.760 --> 00:58:58.560
minutes to run.

00:58:58.560 --> 00:59:02.639
I read the review and then I copy paste the review back into the agent that wrote the

00:59:02.639 --> 00:59:02.959
commit.

00:59:02.959 --> 00:59:04.239
And I'm like, fix this.

00:59:04.239 --> 00:59:05.280
And it fixes it.

00:59:05.280 --> 00:59:06.800
And, um, so that's pretty cool.

00:59:07.520 --> 00:59:08.320
So check it out.

00:59:08.320 --> 00:59:13.040
Um, speaking of like the transcription thing, another thing I did over the holidays, um,

00:59:13.040 --> 00:59:19.360
I always wanted to have, uh, transcripts and like, um, basically just like descriptions

00:59:19.360 --> 00:59:21.520
about talks that I've given in the past.

00:59:21.520 --> 00:59:28.959
So I used Claude, um, to transcribe, um, every talk that I've ever given, um, that has a

00:59:28.959 --> 00:59:34.560
video online and, um, generate a transcript and generate, uh, like a 500 word summary,

00:59:34.560 --> 00:59:36.320
500 words or less of the talk.

00:59:36.959 --> 00:59:42.560
Um, and it did it, uh, use whisper to transcribe and then use Claude to, to summarize.

00:59:43.199 --> 00:59:48.159
And, uh, yeah, that's all on my website now, which is, uh, yeah, it's mostly for me, but

00:59:48.159 --> 00:59:49.600
I, I found it very satisfying.

00:59:49.600 --> 00:59:54.080
And it's like one of those, those things where I could never have justified the expense or

00:59:54.080 --> 00:59:55.439
the time to do that in the past.

00:59:55.439 --> 00:59:57.040
And now, now it's done.

00:59:57.040 --> 01:00:01.919
And I actually had a podcast that I recorded that was released this morning and I, you

01:00:01.919 --> 01:00:03.040
know, fired up the agent.

01:00:03.600 --> 01:00:09.120
I said, here's the YouTube link of this podcast that I did transcribe it, summarize it according

01:00:09.120 --> 01:00:11.600
to my preferences, which are in the Claude MD file.

01:00:12.159 --> 01:00:14.879
Um, and, uh, push it to my website.

01:00:14.879 --> 01:00:19.199
Um, oh, I reviewed it first and I pushed it manually, but you know, get it ready to push.

01:00:19.199 --> 01:00:22.719
Um, and it took about five minutes and, uh, voila, it was done.

01:00:22.719 --> 01:00:24.000
So pretty cool stuff.

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:24.500
Freaky.

